EDITORIAL

Fright, but not paranoia,
should be a part of Halloween

“Trick or treat!”

Wednesday night, we’ll hear children
saying this. Perhaps they’ll even knock
on the doors of students who live off-
campus.

But thanks to terrorism, anthrax
scares and paranoia, some places are can-
celing or discouraging trick-or-treating.

According to the Oct. 25 Pittsburgh
Post-Gazette, Wilkinsburg Mayor
Wilbert Young canceled this Halloween
ritual two weeks ago and replaced it with
community parties, citing worries about
terrorist_ attacks and anthrax threats. He
has since reversed this decision.

But Wilkinsburg is not the only place
that expressed concern about safety.
According to Time magazine, Arkansas
Gov. Mike Huckabee, while not abolish-
ing trick-or-treating in the state, has asked
trick-or-treaters to attend other activities.
His reason: “We can’t handle the panic
that comes when a parent encounters a
broken Pixy Stick in a sack and thinks it
is anthrax.”

The Sept. 11 terrorist attacks and the
recent anthrax scares have put the United
States on edge. At the same time, our
leaders have told us repeatedly to carry
on with our normal lives. It should be no
different for Halloween.

Halloween is a quintessential part of

American life and lore. Although its 011'-
gins lie in Druid and Catholic holidays, it
has become a holiday with a great deal of
American pop-culture signiﬁcance.

This is not the first time there has
been urmecessary fright on Halloween.
For example, in the 1970s a Houston man
named Ronald O’Bryan laced his son’s
candy with cyanide. Because of this, ‘par-
ents learned to be more cautious. They
now inspect their children’s candy every
year, and adults tell their kids not to eat
any before their parents do this. But fears

‘that this might happen again in other

places did not end nick-or-treating, and
